===Etymology===
Comes from Arabic ﺮﺏﻥﺀ ''khanbar'' (the 'kh' representing a fricative aspirant), meaning "ambergris." The ambergris, of animal origin, somehow became confused with the fossil resin, of vegetable origin, so the French language differentiated them as ''ambre gris'', grey amber and ''ambre jaune'', yellow amber. [[English language|English]] adopted this differentiation in the form of respectively, ambergris and amber. The German language adopted respectively, ''Amber'' (or ''Ambra'')  and ''Bernstein''.

